{
  "texts": [
    "Adversarial models such as GAIN rely on a discriminator to distinguish observed from imputed entries, capturing complex nonlinear dependencies [18].",
    "Diffusion models offer another route by reversing a noise process, yielding high-quality, multimodal imputations for tabular data (e.g., TabDDPM) [20].",
    "Although highly accurate, these neural approaches can be computationally demanding.Uncertainty has deep roots in statistics and machine learning.",
    "Frequentist tools quantify sampling variability via confidence and prediction intervals [32], [33], whereas Bayesian inference represents parameter and predictive uncertainty through posteriors [34].",
    "In ML, concerns about overconfidence revived attention to calibration and to the distinction between aleatory and epistemic uncertainty [21]."
  ]
}